atrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["(Welsh)  See  Llewelyn ."],"variants":[{"name":"Llewelyn","meanings":["Traditional: altered form (influenced by <i>llew</i> ‘lion’) of <i>Llywelyn</i>, an ancient name of uncertain derivation. It probably goes back to the Old Celtic name <i>Lugobelinos</i>, the first element of which is <i>Lugu-</i> (the name of a god;  see  Lleu  ); the second is a name-forming element found also in names such as <i>Cunobelinus</i> (<i>Cymbeline</i>). The name was borne by  Llywelyn ap Iorwerth  (  1173–1240 ) and his grandson Llywelyn ap Gruffydd (  d. 1282 ), Welsh princes who for a time united their countrymen in North Wales and led opposition to the power of the Norman barons in South Wales and the Marches."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Loving’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Llywelyn ap Dolphyn was born about 0995, in Wales, his father, Dolphyn ap Llewelyn Eurdorchog, was -43 and his mother, Mrs. Dolphyn ap Llewelyn, was 17. He had at least 2 daughters with Tangwystl ferch Iorwerth."},"et":{"about 0995–":"umbes 0995–Surnud","0995–Male":"0995–Surnud","1060–Male":"1060–Surnud","1002–Female":"1002–Surnud","1024–1119":"1024–1119","1030–1065":"1030–1065","1040–Male":"1040–Surnud","0980–Female":"0980–Surnud","1065":"1065","1030":"1030","1040":"1040","1060":"1060","0995":"0995","about 0995":"umbes 0995","from 1015 to 1020":"1015 kuni 1020","1024":"1024","1002":"1002","0980":"0980","about 1024":"umbes 1024","0998":"0998","1119":"1119","Cardigan, Wales":"Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Dyffryn, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","Dyffryn Clwyd, Wales":"Clwyd, Wales, United Kingdom","Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales","Powys, Wales":"Wales"},"fi":{"about 0995–":"noin 0995–Kuollut","0995–Male":"0995–Kuollut","1060–Male":"1060–Kuollut","1002–